POLITICS AND PEDAGOGY -- t10. In This War But Not of It: Teaching, Memory, and the Futures of Children and War -- t11. “Coffins after Coffins”: Screening Wartime Atrocity in the Classroom -- tAfterword: Scholarship on Millennial and Post-Millennial Culture during the War on Terror: A Bibliographic Essay -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFollowing the 9/11 attacks, approximately four million Americans have turned eighteen each year and more than fifty million children have been born. These members of the millennial and post-millennial generation have come of age in a moment marked by increased anxiety about terrorism, two protracted wars, and policies that have raised questions about the United States's role abroad and at home. Young people have not been shielded from the attacks or from the wars and policy debates that followed. Instead, they have been active participants—as potential military recruits and organizers for social justice amid anti-immigration policies, as students in schools learning about the attacks or readers of young adult literature about wars. The War of My Generation is the first essay collection to focus specifically on how the terrorist attacks and their aftermath have shaped these new generations of Americans. Drawing from a variety of disciplines, including anthropology, sociology, cultural studies, and literary studies, the essays cover a wide range of topics, from graphic war images in the classroom to computer games designed to promote military recruitment to emails from parents in the combat zone. The collection considers what cultural factors and products have shaped young people's experience of the 9/11 attacks, the wars that have followed, and their experiences as emerging citizen-subjects in that moment. Revealing how young people understand the War on Terror—and how adults understand the way young people think—The War of My Generation offers groundbreaking research on catastrophic events still fresh in our minds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPolitical culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aPopular culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aWar and societyzUnited States. 0aWar on Terrorism, 2001-2009xInfluence. 0aWar on Terrorism, 2001-2009xSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aYouthzUnited StatesxSocial conditionsy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAdelman, Rebecca A.1 aAdelman, Rebecca A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Robertson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Robertson.1 aBrowder, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrowder, Laura.1 aClark, Cindy Dell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Cindy Dell.1 aCooper, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Benjamin.1 aGarza, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarza, Irene.1 aKieran, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKieran, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKieran, David.1 aLampert, Jo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLampert, Jo.1 aMaira, Sunaina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaira, Sunaina.1 aSaucier, Jeremy K.1 aSaucier, Jeremy K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSwyers, Holly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSwyers, Holly.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066615140uht